Title:
WerWolf — In-memory BOF implementation of Silent Process Exit LSASS dumping

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
WerWolf is a Windows credential-dumping tool that triggers LSASS minidump creation using the Silent Process Exit technique via `RtlReportSilentProcessExit` (popularized at DEF CON 30). Its main contribution is delivery: the technique is executed as an in-memory Beacon Object File (BOF) loaded by a custom Python COFF loader, avoiding a dropped EXE and avoiding PowerShell-based artifacts (script block logging/AMSI). The dump is written by WerFault/WER to `C:\Windows\Temp\` and can be parsed offline (e.g., with pypykatz). The repo includes a COFF parser/loader in Python and a precompiled BOF (`wer_execute.o`) plus source. It’s primarily useful for red teams and pentesters evaluating EDR visibility around WER-based dumping and in-memory tradecraft.

Technical Focus:
- Silent Process Exit / Windows Error Reporting (WER) LSASS dumping
- `RtlReportSilentProcessExit` invocation and WerFault dump generation
- In-memory BOF execution via custom COFF loader (Python ctypes)
- Registry modifications required for Silent Process Exit behavior
- Operational considerations around async dump creation and file polling

Use Cases:
- Dump LSASS via WER/Silent Process Exit without dropping a standalone executable
- Avoid PowerShell-based implementations to reduce script logging/AMSI exposure
- Red-team tradecraft testing of EDR detections around WerFault/WER dump activity
- Offline credential extraction from generated minidumps (e.g., pypykatz)
- Researching COFF/BOF loading and in-memory execution patterns on Windows

Keywords:
WerWolf, Silent Process Exit, LSASS dump, RtlReportSilentProcessExit, Windows Error Reporting, WER, WerFault.exe, minidump, BOF, Beacon Object File, COFF loader, ctypes, in-memory execution, registry modification, T1003.001, T1112, T1218, pypykatz, Windows 10, Windows Server 2016+